{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458267,"nonce":"9N9x/NCqY9OFOAZ30OFe1sdrhDs=","title":"Training runtime optimization: compilation, TPU performance, adversarial loop fusion","message":"Cross-cutting optimization issue for training pipeline performance. These optimizations affect all experiments that use adversarial training (Part 2, Part 2.5, Part 3).\n\n## Known issues\n\n### 1. 14-minute compilation for adversarial gradient\nThe adversarial training loop involves computing gradients of the adversary loss, which triggers a long XLA compilation pass (~14 minutes on first run). This is likely due to the adversary gradient computation creating a large computation graph that XLA struggles to optimize. Repeated compilations occur when any model shape or hyperparameter changes.\n\n### 2. 12 host-TPU round-trips per training step\nThe current adversarial training loop structure requires multiple host-TPU synchronization points per step (for alternating controller/adversary updates, loss evaluation, gradient application). Each round-trip adds latency, and with 12 per step the overhead is substantial. Fusing operations to reduce round-trips could significantly improve throughput.\n\n### 3. fori_loop fusion fix\nJAX `fori_loop` should allow fusing the inner adversarial optimization steps into a single compiled kernel, eliminating intermediate host-TPU round-trips. However, the current implementation may not be structured to take advantage of this. Restructuring the adversarial inner loop to use `fori_loop` (or `lax.scan`) properly could reduce round-trips from 12 to ~2 (one forward pass, one backward pass).\n\n## Approach\n- Profile the full training step to identify the exact bottlenecks\n- Restructure adversarial inner loop for `fori_loop`/`lax.scan` fusion\n- Investigate XLA compilation flags or graph simplification for the adversary gradient\n- Consider `jax.checkpoint` to trade compute for memory and potentially simplify the graph\n- Test on TPU v4 vs v5e for compilation time differences\n\n## Cross-references\n- Part 2.5 experiments: c05998e, e81f491\n- Worst-case training methods: 84ee4ff\n- Training method comparison: 753508c, a3edc0c","files":null}]}